The extended X-ray absorption fine structure (EXAFS) measurements at the Fe K-edge were carried out at room temperature at the Energy Scanning EXAFS beamline (BL-9) at the Indus-2 Synchrotron source (2.5 GeV, 250 mA) at the Raja Ramanna Centre for Advanced Technology (RRCAT), Indore, India [14,15]. The EXAFS measurement at the Fe K-edge (at 7112 eV) was performed in the fluorescence mode by placing the sample at an angle of 45° relative to the direction of the incident beam. For the data collection in the fluorescence mode, an ionization chamber filled with a predetermined gas mixture was used to measure the incident flux (I 
                        0) prior to the sample, while a Si drift detector placed at 90° relative to the incident beam was employed to measure the fluorescence signal (If
                        ) from the sample. The X-ray absorption coefficient of the sample was determined by µ = [If/I0], which was obtained as a function of energy by scanning the monochromator over a specific energy range.

The thicker solid sheet samples are unable to undergo energy transfer interaction with the graphene quantum dots and hence the emission yield from the F7 and F9 samples is only 18%, which was originated from GQDs present in the corresponding samples. The schematic representation presented in Fig. 5
                        , demonstrates the FRET interaction between the GQD donor and solid sheet acceptor. The time-dependent PL emission decay profiles (Fig. 6
                        ) were measured and fitted with a tri-exponential decay curve. The fitting values and calculated average lifetime values are presented in Table T2. The calculated average PL lifetime value of GQD solid sheet sample separated from F5 raw sample is 6.83 ns and it is increased to 8.55 ns upon addition of GQDs. On a closer look at the individual lifetime components, one can see that there is an increase in the values of lifetime components and the contribution percentage of longer lifetime components as well. The increase in the value of acceptor lifetime upon addition of donor confirms the energy transfer interaction between them [43]. The PL emission lifetime analysis thus clearly demonstrated the occurrence of FRET interaction between Fe interconnected GQD solid sheets and GQDs. The observation of FRET in the solid sheet sample indirectly indicates that the as-formed graphene quantum dot coupled solid sheets are retaining the energy bandgap of GQDs even after becoming larger-sized graphene nanosheet. The energy bandgap opened nature provides the capability for this material to absorb photons in the visible (410 nm) range and so one can use it at places where photon interaction is required to induce optoelectronic properties. Because of the absence of the energy bandgap, pristine graphene cannot interact with visible photons and therefore its use as active material in the fabrication of optoelectronic devices is limited. Our as-prepared GQD solid sheet has given a solution to this scientific problem.
